summary:
The Security Council adopted Resolution 1614 (2005) on 29 July 2005, recalling previous resolutions on Lebanon, including 425 (1978) and 426 (1978), and the statements of its President. The Council:

1. Endorses the report of the Secretary-General on UNIFIL of 21 July 2005;
2. Extends the present mandate of UNIFIL until 31 January 2006;
3. Reiterates its support for Lebanon's territorial integrity, sovereignty, and political independence;
4. Condemns all acts of violence across the Blue Line, urges parties to respect the line, and refrain from provocations;
5. Reiterates its call on parties to respect the withdrawal line and exercise restraint;
6. Calls on the Government of Lebanon to extend its authority throughout the south, including through deployment of sufficient armed and security forces;
7. Welcomes the Secretary-General's intention to discuss with the Lebanese Government the next steps in preparing for an expansion of its authority in the south;
8. Supports UNIFIL's efforts to maintain the ceasefire through patrols and observation;
9. Welcomes UNIFIL's contribution to mine clearance, encourages further assistance, and stresses the necessity of providing existing maps and minefield records to Lebanon and UNIFIL.
1614 (2005)

The Security Council:

10. Calls on parties to ensure UNIFIL has full freedom of movement, requests UNIFIL to report any obstruction, and reiterates its call on parties to cooperate fully with the UN and UNIFIL;

11. Welcomes UNIFIL's efforts to implement the Secretary-General's zero-tolerance policy on sexual exploitation and abuse, requests the Secretary-General to take necessary actions, and urges troop-contributing countries to take preventive and disciplinary actions;

12. Requests the Secretary-General to consult with Lebanon and other parties on implementation, and report to the Council before the end of the mandate on UNIFIL's activities and UNTSO's tasks;

13. Intends to regularly review UNIFIL's mandate and structures, considering the situation on the ground, activities performed, and views of the Lebanese Government;

14. Looks forward to the early fulfilment of UNIFIL's mandate;

15. Stresses the need for a comprehensive, just, and lasting peace in the Middle East, based on relevant resolutions, including 242 (1967) and 338 (1973).
